[1
Date: 11 Dec 2000 04:19:22 -0800 (PST)
From: Shamsudeen Fagbo, DVM <oloungbo@yahoo.com>
Source: Arab News, Sun, 10 Dec 2000 [edited

Ban on Importation of Horses and Birds from France
--------------------------------------------------
RIYADH: Saudi Arabia banned importation of horses and birds from France
yesterday [Sat 9 Dec 2000 over fears of a possible spread of West Nile
virus to the Kingdom, the official Saudi Press Agency reported. It quoted
the Agriculture Ministry as saying the ban was prompted by "cases of horses
affected by West Nile disease, which affects humans and animals in some
parts of France."
It was not immediately clear whether the decision would affect frozen
poultry imports. Saudi Arabia imports some 40 percent of its chicken,
mostly from Brazil and Europe. The country imported an estimated 300 000
tons of chicken in 1998. France has reported cases of horses affected by
West Nile virus in October [2000 in the southern Camargue marshlands, a
major horse-breeding region.
The ministry had banned [previously the importation of horses and birds
from the US State of New York and from Jordan late last month. That order
also followed a report from the Food and Agriculture Organization that said
West Nile fever cases had been detected in these regions. West Nile virus
naturally infects birds and is spread by mosquitoes, which can also carry
it to people. Saudi Arabia is at present battling an outbreak of Rift
Valley fever, another viral disease transmitted from infected livestock to
humans, which has killed 108 people in the Kingdom and at least 97 people
in neighboring Yemen.
--
Shamsudeen Fagbo, DVM
Jeddah, Saudi Arabia
<oloungbo@yahoo.com>
